    <item>
      <title>AI &#43; Social Science Workshop (AIECON 2025)</title>
      <link>https://leoyang.org/talk/ai-social-science-workshop-aiecon-2025/</link>
      <pubDate>Tue, 04 Nov 2025 08:30:00 +0800</pubDate>
      <guid>https://leoyang.org/talk/ai-social-science-workshop-aiecon-2025/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;I joined the &lt;strong&gt;tenth Luojia EMS Frontier Methods Bootcamp &amp;amp; AI + Social Science Workshop&lt;/strong&gt;
to exchange ideas on how generative AI reshapes empirical research in the social sciences.
Hosted by the School of Economics and Management at Wuhan University, the workshop
convened Raymond Duch, Lijia Wei, Lian Xue, Peiran Jiao, and other colleagues for a full day
of methodological training and research dialogue.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;session-highlights&#34;&gt;Session highlights&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;08:30-10:00 - Frontier methods overview.&lt;/strong&gt; Raymond Duch outlined how LLMs can act
as experimental subjects, pollsters, and market analysts, followed by Lijia Wei&amp;rsquo;s evidence on
the Matching-LLM framework for forecasting public opinion.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;10:20-11:50 - Research methods training.&lt;/strong&gt; Lian Xue discussed belief updating with
medical AI explanations, and Peiran Jiao linked employee voice data from Glassdoor to
firm valuation models.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;11:50-12:35 - My presentation.&lt;/strong&gt; I presented &lt;em&gt;Predictive Power, Bias, and Trust:
Evaluating LLM-Driven Screening in FinTech Lending&lt;/em&gt;, showing how model governance and
human oversight mitigate screening bias.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;14:00-16:00 - Roundtable discussion.&lt;/strong&gt; Speakers stayed on for a closed-door session to
trade implementation lessons on building trustworthy AI workflows for social-science data.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;These conversations fed directly into my ongoing AIECON collaborations on data-centric AI,
regulation, and human-centered evaluation of large language models.&lt;/p&gt;
</description>
    </item>
    
    <item>
      <title>High-Frequency Social Media Data Seminar (JNU)</title>
      <link>https://leoyang.org/talk/high-frequency-social-media-data-seminar-jnu/</link>
      <pubDate>Wed, 22 Oct 2025 00:00:00 +0800</pubDate>
      <guid>https://leoyang.org/talk/high-frequency-social-media-data-seminar-jnu/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;Invited by the &lt;strong&gt;Jinan University Social Survey Center&lt;/strong&gt;, I delivered Lecture 55 in the
&amp;ldquo;Social Survey &amp;amp; Application&amp;rdquo; series on the policy shock created by Weibo&amp;rsquo;s April 2022 IP
disclosure requirement. The project tracks 200 news accounts and the top comment chains
around each post to observe how geography-linked identity cues steer civic debate.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;research-overview&#34;&gt;Research overview&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Data engineering.&lt;/strong&gt; I detailed the pipeline we built to capture pre/post policy posts,
scrape reply trees, and annotate user locations while protecting user privacy.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Behavioral impact.&lt;/strong&gt; Comparing domestic and overseas commenters reveals divergent
participation patterns once location tags become visible, alongside a measurable drop in
hostile replies.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Implications for moderators.&lt;/strong&gt; Location transparency changes how online communities
interpret credibility and allegiances, so we discussed how to pair machine flags with human
review to keep deliberation open while curbing abuse.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;We closed with a Q&amp;amp;A on fielding API-rate constraints, validating location cues, and extending
the design to other high-frequency social platforms.&lt;/p&gt;
</description>
    </item>
    
